.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.HOUR" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.hour \- Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.hour
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]hour\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns an integer from 0 to
23 representing the hour component of this time.
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]hour\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
Use the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to create a new
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object with the desired new value.
.PP
For general information and more examples, see
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime.prototype.hour\f[R].
.PP
For \f[CR]ZonedDateTime\f[R], \f[CR]hour\f[R] can be non\-continuous due
to offset changes such as daylight saving time transitions.
In this case, the hour may be repeated or skipped.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using hour
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2021\-07\-01T12:34:56.123456789\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.hour); \f[I]// 12\f[R]
.EE
.SS Non\-continuous hour
Non\-continuous hour is very common due to daylight saving time
transitions, which is explained more in Ambiguity and gaps from local
time to UTC time.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-11\-03T01:59:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.hour); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = dt.add({ minutes: 1 });
console.log(dt2.hour); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
console.log(dt2.toString()); \f[I]// 2024\-11\-03T01:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\f[R]

\f[B]const\f[R] dt3 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-03\-10T01:59:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt3.hour); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt4 = dt3.add({ minutes: 1 });
console.log(dt4.hour); \f[I]// 3\f[R]
console.log(dt4.toString()); \f[I]// 2024\-03\-10T03:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For this reason, you should always prefer \f[CR]add()\f[R] and
\f[CR]subtract()\f[R] to manipulate dates and times, rather than
directly changing the \f[CR]hour\f[R] property.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
